{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501068"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:22:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:22:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1716"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1716"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.21,0.05,0.01,0.7]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1716"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109303"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1716"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1716"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91667"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"348"},{"type":"tags","id":"6621"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1214"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2730"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40805"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109303"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with difficulty using his left hand. This started suddenly this morning, and lasted for three hours, and then slowly resolved without intervention. He described being unable to make a fist with his left hand during the episode and also noticed blurry vision in his right eye for about 20 minutes during the episode. He also reports a similar episode occurring three weeks prior, with the weakness in his left hand resolving completely after two hours. On examination in ED, he appears well and is afebrile. His power was 5/5 for all movements in his upper limbs bilaterally. His visual fields were intact bilaterally and his visual acuity was 6/6 using his correctional lenses. A fundoscopy showed copper wiring bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following abnormalities is most likely to be present on further physical examination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Absent lower limb pulses bilaterally","An irregularly irregular pulse","A diastolic murmur in the mitral area","Left calf tenderness","A right-sided carotid bruit"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has presented with episodic, sudden-onset neurological dysfunction that has resolved spontaneously. This is most consistent with a vascular aetiology, such as a transient ischemic attack (TIA) syndrome. The fact that the dysfunction is not permanent makes a stroke syndrome less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe also has evidence of end-organ damage from longstanding hypertension (copper wiring on fundoscopy). Uncontrolled hypertension is a risk factor for TIA/stroke and a risk factor for developing atherosclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn terms of localising the vascular aetiology:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis left-hand weakness suggests his right motor cortex is affected (supplied by the right middle cerebral artery).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis right eye blurriness could be due to transient monocular\u00a0blindness, which represents amaurosis fugax (caused by transient occlusion of the right central retinal artery supplying the right optic nerve).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransient ischaemic attacks can occur from underlying athero-embolic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is likely that the right side of his anterior cerebral circulation is responsible for his symptoms above, most likely the right common carotid artery. A \u003Cstrong\u003Ebruit heard over the right common carotid artery\u003C/strong\u003E would support underly atherosclerotic disease as the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbsent peripheral pulses would also suggest peripheral arterial disease and likely indicate underlying atherosclerotic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransient ischaemic attacks can also occur from underlying cardio-embolic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAtrial fibrillation (causing an irregularly irregular pulse) is also possible. However, cardiac emboli from atrial fibrillation typically lodge in distal cortical arteries rather than the specific pattern seen here. Additionally, simultaneous emboli to both the right central retinal artery and the right middle cerebral artery territory would be unlikely to originate from a cardiac source.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA new murmur could suggest a diagnosis of infective endocarditis, which can send off septic emboli. However, the patient is afebrile and appears well (without features of infection), so this is less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeft calf tenderness could suggest a left-sided below-knee DVT. This could cause a pulmonary embolism, but would not cause a stroke (unless the patient has a patent foramen ovale - very rare).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Platelet emboli from a carotid artery plaque are a common cause of transient ischaemic events"],"references":["Kim JS, Caplan LR. Clinical Stroke Syndromes. Frontiers of Neurology and Neuroscience. 2016; 40: 72-92.","Kamel H, Healey JS. Cardioembolic Stroke. Circ Res. 2017 Feb 3;120(3):514-526. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28154101/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91667"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1716"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91667"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-19T19:26:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-19T19:27:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1716"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109303"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/348"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Transient ischaemic attack","synonyms":["TIA","Transient ischemic attack"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"